ns normal intestinal barrier function","Results from pancreatic enzyme deficiency","Similar to coeliac disease but caused by infection","Shows no response to antibiotic therapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETropical sprue is an acquired condition characterised by malabsorption and nutritional deficiencies. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimilar to coeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E, it causes villous atrophy and inflammation of the small intestine, but is triggered by infection rather than gluten sensitivity. The condition is not \u003Cstrong\u003Edue to pancreatic enzyme deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Elactase deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E, though secondary lactose intolerance may develop.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003ETropical sprue \u003Cstrong\u003Edoes respond to antibiotic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly tetracyclines, along with folate supplementation. The condition causes significant damage to the intestinal mucosa and therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Edoes not maintain normal intestinal barrier function\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to malabsorption of multiple nutrients including folate, vitamin B12, and fat-soluble vitamins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tropical sprue is an infectious enteropathy causing malabsorption through small intestinal mucosal injury","Tropical sprue responds to antibiotics and folate supplementation","Tropical sprue causes villous atrophy similar to coeliac disease but is triggered by infection rather than gluten"],"references":["DuPont HL. Persistent Diarrhea: A Clinical Review. JAMA. 2016 Jun 28;315(24):2712-23. doi: 10.1001/jama.2016.7833. PMID: 27357241","Nemeth V, Pfleghaar N. Diarrhea. [Updated 2022 Nov 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448082/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u00